<paragraph blockId="59.[370,1859,439,1072]" pageId="59" pageNumber="98">Alulae with a dense fringe of squamose hairs. Wings narrow to quite broad; second submarginal cell closed and short petiolate; first posterior cell broadly open; posterior crossvein usually present, atrophied or absent in a few species; axillary lobe about as broad as long; ambient vein complete.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[370,1859,439,1072]" box="[462,845,683,721]" pageId="59" pageNumber="98">Length, 15-60 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="98" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="59.[370,1859,439,1072]" pageId="59" pageNumber="98">Geographic range: Canada to southern South America (but not found in Chile).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="98" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="59.[370,1859,439,1072]" pageId="59" pageNumber="98">
An extremely varied genus. The most consistent characters are the form of the proboscis and the location of the oral margin opposite the lower eye margin. These are also characters of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bigot" authorityName="Bigot" box="[1466,1852,941,980]" class="Insecta" family="Mydidae" genus="Phyllomydas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<taxonomicName box="[1466,1720,941,979]" class="Insecta" family="Mydidae" genus="Phyllomydas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1466,1720,941,979]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="98">Phyllomydas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bigot
</taxonomicName>
, but its broad face and gibbosity, and its unique female terminalia, separates it quite readily from 
<emphasis box="[936,1074,1033,1071]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="98">
<taxonomicName box="[936,1067,1033,1071]" class="Insecta" family="Mydidae" genus="Mydas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mydas</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
